In Indonesia, after the earthquake, more than 100 prisoners fled the prison
More than 100 prisoners fled the prison in the Indonesian province of Central Sulawesi.
The escape was possible after two powerful earthquakes on the island with a 7.2 and 7.4 magnitude.
According to The Jakarta Post, the incident took place on September 28, when the prisoners in the prison of the city of Palu demanded them to be released due to underground shocks.
More than 340 prisoners revolted and set the institution on fire.
The police who arrived at the place of emergency partially took control of the situation, but more than 100 people escaped from prison.
The building itself was seriously damaged, and the guards hardly manage to hold the prisoners.
The number of earthquake victims and tsunami that occurred on the island of Sulawesi increased to 832 people.
In this regard, it is still not possible to install transport, electricity and communication with some areas of the island.
