Kosachev: Russia's negative topic was practically absent at the 73rd session of the UN General Assembly
Konstantin Kosachev, head of the Federation Council's Foreign Affairs Committee, considers the 73rd session of the UN General Assembly successful for Russia and does not rule out that it will be able to become a turning point in the perception of the Russian Federation as an integral participant in solving global world problems.
"The uniqueness of the current 73rd session, in my opinion, is that the rhetoric, to which we have almost been used in recent years with regard to Russia, has now been magnified," the Senator said in an interview published on Sunday by the Rossiyskaya Gazeta newspaper.
He explained that in previous years Russia was sometimes "signed as one of the three main threats to humanity, along with the fever of Ebola, along with climate change or terrorism, Russia was in this row, at least in the statement of a group of Western countries, which expressed quite unanimously on this account."
At the 73rd session, Kosachev stressed, "Russia's topic was practically absent in a negative way."
"If we carefully analyze the speech of the President of the United States, the President of France, the speech of the German Foreign Minister, I do not take Ukraine, Georgia, or the British, at least, the choir was not exactly accurate," the politician noted, noting that Russia "was not a kind of wall, which is trained by the strikes of tennis ball."
The head of the Sovfed Committee does not rule out that this indicates a certain trend, which, in his opinion, "will be to allocate the current session [the UN General Assembly], although this trend may fully manifest in a year, in two, three."
Kosachev admitted, "I do not exclude that the current session may be a turning point in a way," Kosachev admitted, explaining that "too many examples of Russia's involvement in international affairs."
As an example, he cited the situation in Syria, around Iran and North Korea.
"Unfortunately, this is not Ukraine, but I have no doubt that the Russian vision of the Ukrainian crisis will also be in demand over time," the parliamentarian added.
This is due to the fact that "adequate, sound perception of Russia as not just possible - an integral participant in solving global problems of modern times."
"I don't want to make a mistake, but I have the feeling that we are going through somewhere a point behind which the movement will no longer be a reversal, it will be a move forward," he added.
In this context, Kosachev described another "interesting and important feeling" as "a request for the Russian vision of how the modern world should develop."
"I attended many meetings of the head of the Russian delegation [at the session of the General Assembly] Foreign Minister Sergei Lavrov, I held my own meetings, and I saw with great pleasure that if another year or twenty years ago, the Russian opinion, the Russian vision of what is happening in the world, by and large, no one was interested, now the situation is different," said the chairman of the committee of the Council of Europe.
In his opinion, this is due to the fact that "the so-called new liberal order, which personifies with the West, there are no answers to questions about how to solve the world problems due to the obvious deficit of ideas in the global space, the deficit of ideas on how to solve the problems of the Middle East, the problems of terrorism, the problem of non-proliferation of nuclear weapons, the problem of migration."
Kosachev expressed his confidence: "And here the request for the Russian vision is becoming more and more obvious," stressing that in this regard, "the current session is successful for the work of the Russian delegation, successful for Russia."
