AdG became the second most popular in Germany
The anti-immigrant "Alternative for Germany" hits another record of popularity, and the ratings of Angela Merkel fall.
Apparently, the Germans began to be seriously tired of the immigration policy of Angela Merkel, thanks to which the country became a coveted target for millions of refugees from the Middle East.
The latest polls speak most of all about this, according to which the anti-immigrant party "Alternative for Germany" is becoming more popular, and the positions of the ruling bloc Merkel and Seehofer weaken.
This week, AdG broke another record, rising to the second place in the ranking of popular sympathies.
The right-wing conservatives with 17 percent of popularity managed to bypass the social democrats, who have about 16% of the popularity.
The gap in one percentage point can be attributed to a statistical error, but it should not be noted that the established in 2013 AdG from a small group of economists-Eurological scientists managed to turn into a serious political force.
Leadership in the overall standings continues to hold the ruling bloc CSU/CDU, which has about 30 percent.
However, there is a tendency to lose points - in April, the support of the block of Angela Merkel was four percentage points higher.
The personal rating of the German Chancellor, who heads the German government for the fourth consecutive term, also decreases.
Today, 48% of Germans are in support of Angela Merkel, which is 7% lower than last year.
We would like to add that the social democrats are "green" (15%), left (11%) and liberals (10%).
The Evolution of "Alternatives"
The "Alternative for Germany" Party was established in September 2012 on the basis of the "Alternative Choice 2013" group, which included migrants from the Christian-Democratic Union.
The group initially took the opposition to the government course, but at first it dealt only with economic issues, including the problems of the euro and cooperation within the EU.
At the same time, the group opposed the "sponsoring" of the weak EU economies by Germany, did not exclude the possibility of returning to the German brand and the complete exit of the country from the European Union.
Against the background of the deepening of the immigration crisis, the AdG's political platform has expanded.
In 2013, the group became a full-fledged party, which occupied the niche of Eurosceptics and began harshly criticizing the government for the failure of immigration policy.
At the last parliamentary elections in 2017, AdG managed to get into the Bundestag for the first time, having received 94 deputy seats (out of 709).
Two representatives of the "Alternatives for Germany" get a seat in the European Parliament.
