Experts came to such conclusions, observing with the help of the camera HSC (Hyper Suprime-Cam) telescope Subaru for about ten million galaxies.
After tracking the distribution of dark matter and dark energy, which accounts for more than 95 percent of the energy-mass of the observed world, scientists, working within the framework of the standard cosmological model of the Cold Dark Matter, assessed the pace of the expansion of the Universe, which was slightly slower than previously believed.
In the press release of the Observatory Subaru noted that observations allowed to obtain a detailed three-dimensional map of distribution of matter in the universe, and the data of the European space telescope Planck specified the limitations imposed on the parameters of the ECDM.
